• Storage Virtual machines for NFS and CIFS (ECT = 40 minutes)
	○ Create a Storage Virtual Machine.
	○ Configure the Storage Virtual Machine for CIFS and NFS access.
	○ Create a volume on the Storage Virtual Machine.
	○ Mount a CIFS share from the Storage Virtual Machine on a Windows client.
	○ Mount an NFS volume from the Storage Virtual Machine on a Linux client.
	○ Create and NFS-export Qtrees. (Optional)


SVM: 
To provide the storage or provision the storage
Create separate SVMs for NAS and SAN storage and identify the protocols
	
Create NAS SVM: 
SVM Name: svm-nas
Data Protocols: CIFS, NFS Protocols
Volume Security Style: NTFS, UNIX, Mixed
Root aggregate: select aggregate
DNS Configuration:
Domain name: demo.netapp.com
Name Server: 192.168.0.253

LIF - Logical interface (It is an IP Address)
Own port, own node, protocols, roles
When creating LIF assign to a particular port.
Roles: Node Management, Data, Intercluster

SAN FC - A LIF is nothing but WWPN 

Configure CIFS/NFS Protocols:
To enable CIFS, Specify the data interfaces and CIFS server details. 

If you configure NFS, specify the NIS details
To enable access to the NFS ports, add rules to the default export policy or create a new policy for the SVM. 
While creating SVM we need an AD username and passwords

Data Interface(LIF) Configuration:
Assign specific IP address: Using a subnet or without a subnet
Port: Select the cluster

CIFS Server Configuration:
CIFS Server name
AD:
Username
Password

SVM Administration:
Specify the following details to enable host-side applications such as Snap Drive and Snap Manager.
To enable the SVM Administrator to create the volumes. You must assign aggregate to the SVM by using the edit SVM dialog

Note: For Each SVM we need two Data LIFs(node1 & node2) for Data redundancy.

Network --> Network Interfaces --> Create --> 

To enable DNS on Each LIF to avoid the connectivity issue (Modify network on in CLI)
::> network interface modify -lif <LIF-Name> -vserver <vserver-name> dns zone <DNS Name>







